      &lt;hr /&gt;
&lt;font face=&quot;Tex Gyre Pagella&quot; size=5pt&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align:justify&quot;&gt;
&lt;b&gt;“Evaluating the employment impact of a mandatory job search program” by Richard Blundell, Monica Costa-Dias, Costas Meghir and John van Reenen.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/font&gt; &lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt; &lt;font face=&quot;Tex Gyre Pagella&quot; size=5pt&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align:justify&quot;&gt;
&lt;b&gt;Please, read the paper and answer the following questions:&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/font&gt; &lt;br/&gt; &lt;font face=&quot;MathJax_Math&quot; size=5pt&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align:justify&quot;&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;1. What treatment do the authors evaluate? What is the outcome variable?&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/font&gt; &lt;br/&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;font face=&quot;Tex Gyre Pagella&quot; size=5pt&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align:justify&quot;&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Answer 1.1: &lt;/b&gt; The authors evaluate the treatment effects of a labor market program called“New Deal for the Young Unemployed”in the UK ,including substitution effects and equilibrium wage effects. The authors especially focus on the degree to which the “Gateway” has lead to an increase in outflows into employment.&lt;/p&gt;
    
    </summary>
    
    
